properties.description:
&lt;div&gt;Horizons Plaza 140 Lower Terrace St&lt;br&gt;Buffalo, NY 14240&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;After two feet of snow fell in a single day, the city of Buffalo turned to WNED. The station responded, providing 400,000 affected families with comprehensive reports on downed power lines, the dangers of flooded basements and the proper use of generators and gas stoves&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;701 South Mt. Vernon Avenue&lt;br&gt;San Bernardino, CA 92410-2798&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;For the sake of future generations, KVCR invited local war veterans and survivors to record their wartime experiences. These Reflections on War oral histories are broadcast throughout the year, presented to local VFW conventions and shown at the Palm Springs Air Museum.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;630 Mainstream Drive&lt;br&gt;Nashville, TN 37228-1204&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Nashville Public Radio's Live in Studio C provides classical, jazz and alternative musicians with the only live radio performance opportunity in Middle Tennessee and provides local audiences the opportunity to hear some of the best musical artists in the area.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7140 SW Macadam Avenue&lt;br&gt;Portland, OR 97219&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;OPB's Think Out Loud, a daily call-in and online regional forum, provides a safe, non-partisan place for civil discourse, where the diverse citizens of the Pacific Northwest learn from each other and gain a deeper understanding of complex issues.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;8401 Datapoint Drive, Suite 800&lt;br&gt;San Antonio, TX 78229&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Texas Pubic Radio's multiplatform focus on the environment includes in-person forums on clean air and water, clean ups of several public parks on National Public Lands Day and on-air interviews addressing consumer waste, alternative energy and green building. To provide resources and recreation to injured soldiers at Brooke Army Medical Center, and other area residents with mental, physical, developmental and sensory disabilities, KPAC partners with local non-profits to present the annual AccessAbility Fest. As a result, a local foundation has created a comprehensive online directory of support services.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;365 Troy Avenue&lt;br&gt;Colchester, VT 05446&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;VPR's multiplatform My Vermont project fostered a vibrant discussion of statewide issues - such as affordability, job loss, rising health care costs - using in-depth on-air and online reporting and by soliciting and presenting ideas, questions, aspirations and plans from ordinary citizens. VPR contributes to the Vermont Reads project with on-air essays, performances, documentaries, and user-generated website content. Serving a state with a long history of environmental consciousness, VPR commits to extensive on-air coverage of green issues, publishes eco-friendly tips from listeners on its website and gets 100 percent of its power from renewable resources.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Central Missouri State University, Wood Room 11&lt;br&gt;Warrensburg, MO 64093&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Happy Healthy Missouri Kids In their community leadership summits, KMOS learned that children's health was a high priority for local public officials, agencies and non-profits. In response, the station worked with community health experts to develop a grassroots, multiplatform campaign that encouraged healthy habits for children and families. Local organizations and teachers received kits containing DVDs, games, tips, brochures, even hand sanitizer to help families with meal planning, immunizations, exercise and disease prevention. More than 200 workshops were conducted, reaching 9,000 families. Follow-up surveys indicated that 78% of the attendees were making wiser health choices as a result of participation in trainings and events. As a result of their work, KMOS received an Outstanding Media Partner Award from the Missouri Public Health Association.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7246 Humboldt Hill Road&lt;br&gt;Eureka, CA 95502&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Community Voices For Methamphetamine Awareness As recently as 2007, Humboldt County led California in methamphetamine-related deaths. In response to this crisis, KEET-TV spearheaded a coalition of media, government, education and nonprofit organizations, who together produced television and radio documentaries, public service announcements, street theater and a fact book on resources and treatment. The station has given away hundreds of DVD copies of their Life After Meth documentary to families, schools, libraries and organizations, and local university nursing and social work students view the program in their classes. Life After Meth received a Silver Telly Award and partner station KHUM's radio documentary Picking Up won an Edward R. Murrow Award.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1455 North Orchard&lt;br&gt;Boise, ID 83706&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Legislature Live In response to requests from viewers especially far outside the capitol city of Boise for more extensive coverage of the legislature, Idaho PTV installed robotic cameras in the House and Senate chambers, and began providing gavel-to-gavel coverage via DTV broadcast and online streaming. The station received support and cooperation from the state's Legislative Services and the Idaho State Broadcasters Association (ISBA) to carry out this endeavor. Idaho's many rural residents can now closely follow the progress of bills and laws that affect their businesses and daily lives.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;260 14th Street, NW&lt;br&gt;Atlanta, GA 30318-5360&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Thinking Outside The Box GPB's Efforts to Make Sure No Georgian is Left in the Dark During the DTV Transition The Department of Commerce identified five groups most likely to be adversely affected by the DTV conversion: seniors, the economically disadvantaged, rural residents, people with disabilities and minorities. Georgia Public Broadcasting spearheaded a statewide information campaign to prepare its residents for the transition to digital. They formed a task force of organizations serving minorities, created a coupon-exchange program, connected with public officals across the state, developed an extensive DTV conversion website and produced numerous broadcast PSAs. GPB made a full transition to DTV in February 2009, and now offers four 24-hour digital channels.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1 Clover Court&lt;br&gt;Wixom, MI 48393&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Sphinx Competition Finals Concert For five years, Detroit Public Television has produced and simulcast the dramatic finals concert for the Sphinx Organization's annual competition. The Sphinx Organization is a non-profit founded by Aaron P. Dworkin, a graduate of the Interlochen Arts Academy and the University of Michigan, and a violinist himself, to overcome the cultural stereotypes of classical music and encourage the participation of African American and Latino musicians. The competition offers school-aged musicians the opportunity to perform with professionals and to receive guidance from a renowned panel of judges. Popular with DPTV audiences, the program not only extends the reach of the Sphinx Organization, but has strengthened DPTV's arts partnerships throughout southeast Michigan.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;161 W. Wisconsin Ave., Suite LL1000&lt;br&gt;Milwaukee, WI 53201-0413&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WUWM's Project Milwaukee focuses content and outreach around key community issues. In 2007, the station examined the loss of manufacturing jobs, a minority "brain drain," and dozens of other economic stories. In 2008, the issue was health, and in 2009, race relations.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;67 Bedford Square&lt;br&gt;Pittsburgh, PA 15203&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;To celebrate the city's 250th anniversary, WYEP developed the multiplatform Pittsburgh Performance Project. Listeners voted on the 12 best performance venues and budding radio journalists interviewed favorite musicians, ranging from jazz players, to steel mill rockers to hip-hop stars. In WYEP's FreeZone program, students from some of Pittsburgh's toughest neighborhoods create powerful radio essays about their lives and the issues that matter to them, such as politics, incarcerated parents, aspirations of attending college, sexual abuse and pop culture.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;University of South Florida 4202 East Fowler Ave., TVB 100&lt;br&gt;Tampa, FL 33620-6870&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2008 six proposed amendments to the Florida constitution addressed everything from the definition of marriage to property tax exemptions. WUSF produced a comprehensive series of television, radio and online specials exploring the hotly-contested amendments in detail.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;429 South Shore Drive&lt;br&gt;Grand Marais, MN 55604&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;When a forest fire raged for nearly two weeks, destroying homes and businesses, emergency officials used WITP to broadcast critical evacuation notices. The station followed up with extensive coverage online and on-air, including information about fire-related health issues and financial aid. WTIP is now part of the emergency response team with the sheriff and fire departments.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;429 South Shore Drive&lt;br&gt;Grand Marais, MN 55604&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Responding to audience requests for more health programming, WUNC launched North Carolina Voices: Diagnosing Health Care. The station produced in-depth reports during morning and evening drive time, a series of talk shows, and several public forums across the state, earning recognition by the Association Health Care Journalists.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;480 Cedar St.&lt;br&gt;Saint Paul, MN 55101&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;More than 11,000 "kids and their grown-ups" enjoy MPR's Rock the Cradle event each year. At a local art museum and a children's theatre families experience music together through movement, art, picking up an instrument and listening to live performances. Working with The Citizens League, MPR's The Current developed Policy and a Pint events to engage younger listeners in local issues. MPR talent serve as moderators for lively pub debates, interviews and conversations, and the station follows up with online forums.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;160 Varick Street&lt;br&gt;New York, NY 10013&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WNYC's Street Shots project brought together more than one thousand NYC street photographers to exchange working methods, be profiled on-air and online, and participate in a photo contest using flickr.com, with winning photos exhibited at the New York Camera Club. The photographers continue to connect regularly with each other and the station. To help listeners make meaningful connections in New York, WNYC developed a series of social events for singles only. Hundreds attended sold-out parties held at partner venues, such as the New York City Opera, Chelsea Art Museum and the Brooklyn Brewery, and attracted additional revenue to the station.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;10501 FGCU Blvd.&lt;br&gt;Fort Myers, FL 33965&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Southwest Florida's non-profit organizations struggle to maintain donors and volunteers in a region with a high population turnover. WGCU developed the multiplatform Connect! initiative to help new residents link up with local non-profits, using radio and TV programs, the station magazine and website.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;123 Pitkin Road&lt;br&gt;Plainfield, VT 05667&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WGDR provides intensive media training in technical operations, FCC rules and radio production to community members. The station has trained more than 100 volunteers ranging in age from 12 to 77, including students from a treatment facility for challenged adolescents.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;11510 East Colonial Drive&lt;br&gt;Orlando, FL 32817&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WMFE ensured that Orlando area residents received in-depth coverage of key local elections in 2008. The station showcased candidates for Congress, the Florida House and Senate, County Commissioner and local school boards in Ballot 2008, available on-air, on-demand and on-line.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;983 Reservoir St.&lt;br&gt;Harrisonburg, VA 22801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;When a regional library designated "This I Believe" for its One Book, One Community project, WMRA presented writing workshops and solicited citizen essays for its on-air series The Civic Soapbox. Essays were also given public readings, downloaded as podcasts, and published in print.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;American University Radio, 4000 Brandywine Street, NW&lt;br&gt;Washington, DC 20016-8082&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2008, The Kojo Nnamdi Show tackled public school performance and accountability. The station produced call-ins with local school superintendents, as well as specials on parent activism, school desegregation in Virginia, and the pros and cons of extended school hours.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;54 Park Place&lt;br&gt;Newark, NJ 07102&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;As Newark public schools reduced music education, WBGO filled the gap by producing local Kids Jazz Concerts, creating a quarterly print and online magazine Jazzmatazz, and broadcasting the best college and high school jazz bands in the New York/New Jersey area. The State Council on the Arts honored the station with its two highest awards.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;890 Commonwealth Avenue, 3rd Floor&lt;br&gt;Boston, MA 02215&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Prompted by an historic bill mandating health insurance for every Massachusetts resident, WBUR provided comprehensive reporting through its daily newscasts, call-in programs, special documentaries and a dedicated website. WBUR's coverage earned the Associated Press Public Affairs award for New England.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4600 Cass Avenue&lt;br&gt;Detroit, MI 48201&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Located at the epicenter of the nation's financial crisis, WDET-FM provides accurate, in-depth local economic coverage through Detroit Today. As the challenges also spawn innovation in business development, the program communicates both the adversity and optimism in the city.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;111 James P. Brawley Drive SW&lt;br&gt;Atlanta, GA 30314&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Working with business-oriented partners such as the Atlanta Metropolitan Black Chamber of Commerce and the GA Hispanic Network, WCLK invited community members to be guests on its "Minding Your Money" show, a weekly call-in financial program that addresses finances and economic issues. Community partners were featured in on-air announcements and given the opportunity to discuss future economic-related programming.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2101 S. Main&lt;br&gt;Little Rock, AR 72206&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KABF-FM, serving the minority communities of Little Rock, Ark., consolidated its programming efforts around the economic crisis. Working with the Arkansas Community Housing Corporation and 10 neighborhood associations, the station addressed key economic issues in the area and connected residents with resources provided by community partners. KABF-FM used the grant to organize and broadcast a town hall meeting and created an interactive web page and weekly talk show to extend the engagement.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;500 Mansell Street&lt;br&gt;San Francisco, CA 94134&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With its project "The Economic Edge: Documenting the Downturn," KALW News investigated the effect of the economic crisis in the San Francisco Bay Area by identifying employment opportunities, disseminating information resources and developing a community-generated database of solutions. The station tapped partner organizations to create an open-forum "solutions wiki" and organized citizen reporter street teams to cover local neighborhoods. It also built an online resource amalgamator for job seekers of all situations - youth seeking summer jobs, people who were newly laid-off, and older people coming out of retirement.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2020 South Avenue 8E&lt;br&gt;Yuma, AZ 85366&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With a 20 percent population growth and 56 percent of the population of Hispanic origin, Yuma, Arizona sits at the crossroads of several economically diverse cultures. To assess and define the question "What is Yuma?", KAWC-AM/FM created a program based on NPR's local news initiative "Sense of Place." KAWC and its partners convened a town hall meeting to debate Yuma's sense of identity and assess critical economic issues. The station engaged the community with radio, print and online reports and created a support services fair to connect residents with local resources and businesses.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4455 South Padre Island Drive #38&lt;br&gt;Corpus Christi, TX 78411&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;South Texas has seen a strong downturn in its local economy, especially for lower-income Hispanic families involved in the construction industry. KEDT addressed the way in which local unemployment deeply and often tragically affects the healthcare of young children. Partnering with local health organizations, KEDT coordinated and broadcast live community forums to provide much needed information on the availability of local health services for children, and to de-stigmatize requests for help. In particular, the programs focused on diabetes, as south Texas has the state's highest incidence of the disease.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1808 Riverside Avenue&lt;br&gt;Minneapolis, MN 55454&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KFAI used its partnerships with the Strive To Thrive/Northwest Area Foundation and the Minnesota Spokesman Recorder to address housing and mortgage foreclosures in the Twin Cities. The station, which serves more than 20 ethnically, socially and economically diverse constituencies, conducted a one-day conference and follow-up Webinar that resulted in a multi-faceted action plan. These events were recorded and broadly disseminated via live remote broadcast and online media.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4520 Hanalei Plantation Rd # D&lt;br&gt;Hanalei, HI 96714&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KKCR serves Kauai, a Hawaiian community very dependent on the travel industry. Starting with face-to-face meetings and progressing to town halls, the station recruited partners from ten neighborhoods across the island to discuss Kauai's future, draw up an action plan of self-sufficiency, and apply it with specific goals, objectives, and time-frames for each neighborhood. KKCR also created neighborhood-specific websites to pool information and provided regular progress reports on-air. The station tapped expertise from local residents and businesses to create an action plan for a more economically independent island.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1422 W. Lake Street, Suite 300&lt;br&gt;Minneapolis, MN 55408&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KMOJ provided its listeners with a better understanding of the current economic crisis and how it affects the Twin Cities' business community, the Twin Cities' black business community and the black community as a whole. The station used its weekly talk program Financial Fitness as a vehicle for this project. Keeping with the interactive format of the program KMOJ expanded its community engagement to include blogs and community forums. Working with financial consultants, the station produced special online reports for posting on KMOJs and its partners websites.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Central Missouri State University, Wood Room 11&lt;br&gt;Warrensburg, MO 64093&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KMOS convened an Economic Leadership Summit to identify and discuss the two most pressing economic issues in central Missouri's 38 counties. Partners included Farm Bureaus, local Chambers of Commerce, and family service agencies that convened and developed a community economic coalition that designed an action plan to address the two issues identified. On-air, the station featured a panel of experts recommended by the coalition to answer callers' questions on the KMOS Live! series.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Building 83, Northern Arizona University&lt;br&gt;Flagstaff, AZ 86011-5764&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Northern Arizona's economy was driven by tourism (attracting millions of visitors annually) until the economic downturn caused a 27 percent decline in tourism revenue. KNAU-FM worked with the Arizona Daily Sun, Northern Arizona University's research department and business partners to produce in-depth features that described and framed the situation. The station convened public meetings and created interactive Web forums. The listening public gained an understanding of tourism's role in the regional economy and learned about alternatives to the vulnerable boom-bust cycles of a tourism-based economy.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;5850 Labath Avenue&lt;br&gt;Rohnert Park, CA 94928&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Focusing on already economically depressed neighborhoods in Rohnert Park, California, KRCB staff trained a select group of youth to use video and audio-tape to tell stories about how the current economic crisis affects local families. This project provided at-risk and Hispanic youth with a chance to learn a technical skill while helping their communities, and helped to increase public awareness and discourse so that a sustainable solution could be found. The youth's stories were posted online and incorporated into presentations for local government officials.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3911 South Regal Street&lt;br&gt;Spokane, WA 99223&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With Spokane facing one of the highest unemployment rates in the nation, a reduction of state health care resources by over $1 billion, and 16% of its population below the poverty level, access to community health resources is more vital than ever. In response, KSPS Public Television partnered with Community Minded Enterprises to provide access to the numerous health care resources for the underinsured and uninsured in the viewing area. KSPS conducted a live call-in television broadcasts titled Health Matters, offered online engagement opportunities, as well as on-air interstitials using three digital channels and a community access cable channel.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7733 Perkins Road&lt;br&gt;Baton Rouge, LA 70810&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Louisiana residents have the second lowest credit ratings in the country. To help residents recover, LPB provided online resources for viewers to get their questions answered about economic issues including credit problems, bankruptcy and mortgage foreclosure. Working with the non-profit Credit Bureau of Baton Rouge, LPB identified and promoted links to additional resources. The station also offered a month-long "Ask the Experts" blog, post-Louisiana Public Square chats and a week-long Credit Line Hotline for those without Internet access.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1800 North 33rd Street&lt;br&gt;Lincoln, NE 68503&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;NET expanded its ongoing coverage of the economy in Nebraska through collaboration with the University of Nebraska's Institute of Agriculture and Natural Resources/University Extension. The station created a half-hour "Recession Survival Guide" broadcast with ten outreach events, an hour-long radio call-in program, and extensive online and print resources. Topics of concern identified include tightening lines of credit, falling commodity prices, declining home and property values, as well as the stress and anxiety due to the economy.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2 Pillsbury Street, 6th Floor&lt;br&gt;Concord, NH 03301&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Working It Out is a special initiative of NHPR to help listeners process societal changes brought on by the recession and recovery, as well as promote the best community instincts of cooperation and mutual aid. The station worked with local organizations to build an online forum that identifies local economic issues, and links individuals and organizations together to address particular concerns. The online forum provides a clickable state map that features three layers of information: personal accounts, communities efforts to cope, and an exchange of services and job board.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2350 Dole Street&lt;br&gt;Honolulu, HI 96822&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Although the recession hit Hawaii hard, there was little information on what citizens could do to mitigate the hardship caused by the economic downturn. In response to viewer requests, PBS Hawaii produced two live, hour-long programs dedicated to helping its viewers stave off the effects of a declining economy. One show featured the insights of Hawaii's leading business reporter, and the second provided economic education for youth and seniors. Both programs were viewer-driven and included a panel of local experts answering phone calls, e-mails, and Twitter comments. Viewer ideas were also integrated into follow-up, short-form programs.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;100 Innovation Blvd 120 Outreach Bldg&lt;br&gt;University Park, PA 16802&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WPSU's "Surviving the Housing Crisis" broadcast on TV, FM and online a panel discussion and Q &amp; A about the affects of the unraveling housing market in the viewing and listening area and across Pennsylvania. The panel offered background information and then answered caller and online questions. The program was then archived and segmented online. WPSU also offered a phone bank with Penn State Cooperative Extension educators to answer "off-air" anonymous questions during the broadcast. The station, Extension and The Affordable Housing Coalition also created a Web-based aggregation of resources and tools.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;570 Hostos Avenue&lt;br&gt;San Juan, PR 00919-0909&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In Puerto Rico, the median household income ($18,191) is less than half of U.S. median income ($50,000), and it has been greatly affected by the U.S. economy's downturn, as have many Spanish speaking communities throughout America. WIPR used its program Nueva Economa to focus on the loss of employment and the increase in credit and mortgage debt on the island commonwealth. Partnering with local banks, credit card debt specialists and the credit union association Liga de Cooperativas, WIPR coordinated a workshop for viewers and provided information and answers to financial questions on the stations Web site and blog.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;28 South Fir&lt;br&gt;Medford, OR 97501&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Spearheaded by Southern Oregon Public Television, Southern Oregon Town Hall is an ongoing regional community engagement project that brings opinion leaders and community members together to discuss community issues and uses consensus facilitation to develop strategies to address their concerns. Partnering with local community colleges, the station conducted a new session focusing on the role of education and the economy. The event was broadcast live, featured a panel of experts and offered live phone-in capabilities. The discussion continued online and in follow-up planning meetings.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;172 East Fourth Street&lt;br&gt;St. Paul, MN 55101&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In collaboration with Hamline University, Twin Cities Public Television produced a live roundtable, in which a panel of diverse, well-informed, but non-expert community members discussed the chief economic issues concerning the region. The discussion was be taped and edited for later statewide broadcast as a half-hour special and was made available as streaming video from both organizations' Web sites. The program also connected viewers to pertinent local resources.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Bowling Green State University, 245 Troup Street&lt;br&gt;Bowling Green, OH 43403&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With rising unemployment, closures of auto-related manufacturing facilities, and the failure of new ethanol plants, WBGU-TV initiated discussions to ascertain the economic development issues in its 18-county coverage area. The station expanded this effort through a full-day workshop with approximately 50 community leaders, town hall meetings in four distinct economic regions, and a live call-in program that engaged viewer's comments and ideas for future action. Ultimately a working group created a regional action plan for FY 2010, addressing the top four or five challenges for northwest and west-central Ohio.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;506 Old Liverpool Road&lt;br&gt;Syracuse, NY 13220-2400&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WCNY's 19-county viewing area has the highest unemployment rate in New York State, and many central New Yorkers do not know where to get help through this economic crisis. WCNY therefore created a "Community Intervention" to connect the jobless population with every possible resource for re-employment and financial recovery. The activities included: a televised town hall meeting, a Web page featuring streamed video segments, an interactive forum and a county-specific "Survival Guide for the Unemployed."&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Morgan State University, 1700 East Cold Spring Lane&lt;br&gt;Baltimore, MD 21251&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WEAA-FM has always dedicated an hour a week to promoting financial literacy and encouraging economic empowerment through its Wealthy Lifestyles series. As part of its Engaging Communities on the Economy project, the station expanded the series to include a two-hour special featuring an open forum on the housing crisis, specifically foreclosures, that broadcast and was posted with a bonus segment on the station Web site. The station also created and distributed print materials featuring information from the special for those without access to broadcast or Internet.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;150 North 6th Street&lt;br&gt;Philadelphia, PA 19106&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Current data shows strong evidence of a significant threat to the Greater Philadelphia economy in the education and medical fields, which provide 30% of the areas jobs. Partnering with the University of Pennsylvania Project for Civic Engagement, WHYY convened community-wide forums and workshops that addressed the effects of the economic crisis as it directly relates to these two integral sectors. Community members joined panelists from colleges, medical schools, hospitals, healthcare and pharmaceutical companies in discussions and reports, starting a dialogue that was recorded and broadcast across all platforms.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;283 Communications Arts &amp; Science Bldg, Michigan State University&lt;br&gt;East Lansing, MI 48824&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;After losing 277,000 jobs in 2008, Michigan's 12 percent unemployment rate became the highest in the country. For this reason WKAR Public Media invited community and business leaders to attend a day-long Economic Summit to discuss, identify and prioritize mid-Michigan's economic issues and determine the best ways to offer assistance. The station used online surveys to prioritize the agenda issues and engaged a skilled facilitator to lead the discussions. The project helped WKAR formulate an action plan to help people identify and address their individual needs.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;172 NE 15th Street&lt;br&gt;Miami, FL 33132&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Through its Ready To Learn (RTL) program and in collaboration with the Homestead Police Department, WLRN regularly provides early childhood outreach to Hispanic-migrant and Haitian populations in the South Dade area. By partnering with the Financial Planning Association of Miami-Dade, WLRN expanded its efforts and educated Haitian and Hispanic migrant families about personal finance. Educational sessions were available in Spanish and in Haitian-Creole and offered free childcare. These "Budgeting 101" seminars were recorded and DVDs and print materials in Spanish and Haitian-Creole were available for distribution through local community centers.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;405 Carpenter Street&lt;br&gt;Evansville, IN 47708&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WNIN's Economic Response Project was a regional effort targeting the citizens who were experiencing need for the first time due to the economic downturn, and connecting them to available resources. Joining forces with social service and governmental agencies, WNIN-TV-FM promoted community resources and worked to de-stigmatize family requests for assistance. The station identified the single largest area of need and provided a call-in show for both radio and TV. Activities included blogs, better integrated use of Twitter and Facebook, and links to vital community services on its website.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;160 Varick Street&lt;br&gt;New York, NY 10013&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WNYC convened African Diaspora citizens and influential residents from Brooklyn, New York, and Newark, New Jersey, in strategic discussions on the most pressing economic issues for their communities. WYNC engaged all invitees in advance with a query through its Public Insight Network to identify the central questions and issues for the discussions. WNYC presenters participated in the discussion events which were recorded and streamed online.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1000 ASU Drive #269&lt;br&gt;Alcorn State, MS 39096&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Ninety percent (90%) of the audience in WPRL's service area are African-Americans who live in a rural setting. The per capita income of the service area is less than half of the state rate ($10,500), and the unemployment rate ranges from 13% to 18%, four to five times higher than the state level. WPRL identified and shared the concerns of these residents through surveys and town hall meetings with local government officials. The station also connected residents with assistance from financial advisers, faith-based organizations and local non-profit organizations.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;429 South Shore Drive&lt;br&gt;Grand Marais, MN 55604&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WTIP helped its northern Minnesota listeners gain a clearer understanding of the growing and urgent problem of local hunger and poor nutrition as part of the larger national economic crisis. WTIP convened local officials, groups and individuals in an on-air community conversation focusing on what could be done to address the issue. Afterwards, the station posted the conversation online on a dedicated Web page and continued the discussion on the community's E-Democracy issues blog. A community vegetable garden was also created on the station grounds to demonstrate localism.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;RR 28&lt;br&gt;Dunmore, WV 24934&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;For generations, most young people have left the isolated mountain region of West Virginia to seek work, but even the remaining local lumber and ski industries are suffering in the current economy. WVMR is attempting to address this crisis by partnering with area weekly newspapers, a citizen-based visioning group, and local government officials in a multi-faced dialogue called Create West Virginia. The station is sponsoring community meetings, call-in shows and online dialogues to stimulate community involvement and creativity in seeking new ways for West Virginia to re-think and expand its economic horizons.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;298 Port Republic Road&lt;br&gt;Harrisonburg, VA 22801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WVPT created a Community Engaging Partner Committee and empowered them to create a survey to identify issues relating to the economy in the area. The survey was distributed within the community and the results were compiled to inform the content of television specials under the umbrella of WVPT's local series "Consider This."&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;280 State Street&lt;br&gt;Rochester, NY 14603-3021&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Working with the Greater Rochester Financial Literacy Coalition, WXXI developed the children's finance education series BizKid$. WXXI expanded its efforts to adults, holding listening meetings to hear community concerns and educate Rochester area residents on local economic issues. The station worked with the Center for Governmental Research to understand and contextualize housing, credit and other economic statistics for the Rochester community. WXXI's radio, TV and education staff also produced stories and news specials, and used new media and social networking sites to connect residents with local resources and educational workshops.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;67 Bedford Square&lt;br&gt;Pittsburgh, PA 15203&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Thousands of Pittsburgh students are concerned with paying for college and how the current economy will affect that process. WYEP launched a multimedia educational series that explored what parallels exist between the home mortgage and student loan industries, and what lessons can be learned to prevent a student loan meltdown. Through a series of videos and podcasts, the station created a resource for students to avoid financial pitfalls, and worked with a local financial institution to develop budgeting software aimed at keeping students out of overwhelming student loan debt.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;515 NE 15th Avenue&lt;br&gt;Portland, OR 97232&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;All Classical FM partners with the Oregon Symphony and Portland Opera to host lectures, provide music lessons, and invite listeners to watch pre-recorded concerts online. On air, the station provides behind-the-scenes looks at how art organizations work and insight into performances.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1223 Central Parkway&lt;br&gt;Cincinnati, OH 45214&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WGUC's Classics for Kids - introduces classical music to youngsters in an interactive, entertaining way. In on-air programs, a host uses music to tell a composer's story and illustrate a musical concept. Online, children find interactive musical games and information, and teachers find free lesson plans with 70,000 users visiting the website monthly.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2323 W. 14th St.&lt;br&gt;Tempe, AZ 85281&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KBAQ drives appreciation for the arts by co-sponsoring community events with the Arizona Opera, Ballet Arizona and Phoenix Symphony; promoting arts local dance, lectures, performances and exhibits on-air and online; profiling local composers; and highlighting emerging young classical performers.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;820 Chestnut St.&lt;br&gt;Jefferson City, MO 65102&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KJLU helped the United Way of Central Missouri raise a record $1.6 million for its programs, including the Central Missouri Food Bank. The station produced the community kickoff and created PSA's for use on multiple outlets. KJLU was recognized by the Black College Radio &amp; Television Organization for Radio Station with Most Community Involvement Award.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2323 W. 14th Street&lt;br&gt;Tempe, AZ 85202&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KJZZ's mentoring project for high school journalists, Teen Radio, has inspired a number of program alumni to pursue degrees in broadcast communications. The station also provides opportunities for teens and parents to volunteer together at the station.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;5200 Campanile Drive&lt;br&gt;San Diego, CA 92182&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;For four years, KPBS has used "One Book San Diego" as a catalyst for community engagement and enrichment, sponsoring discussions, lectures and cultural events; providing curriculum for educators; and creating special radio, TV and Web content. The initiative has increased library use and books sales in the city, and secured additional funding for the station.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;528 Ninth Street&lt;br&gt;Alamosa, CO 81101&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Aware that Alamosa's Guatemalan immigrant community faces discrimination, language barriers and cultural isolation, KRZA created Espiritu Maya. This original program provides news and community information in the native Guatemalan language of Q'anjob'al, as well as an array of Guatemalan music. _When salmonella was discovered in Alamosa's drinking water in March 2008, this city of 8,000 had no water for drinking, cooking, or bathing. KRZA was the first to alert residents, and city leaders and health officials used the station to disseminate critical information.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3375 Camino Del Ris So&lt;br&gt;San Diego, CA 92108&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In response to shrinking state education funds for visual and performing arts, and aware that musical accomplishment is linked to academic success, KSDS solicits used instruments from listeners to give to local schools, produces the City College Education Jazz Festival for emerging jazz musicians, and distributes a multimedia Jazz for Young People curriculum.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2408 S. Jackson Street&lt;br&gt;Amarillo, TX 79178&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Texas Panhandle WWII Stories Project Thirty-four Medals of Honor were awarded to natives of the Lone Star state during WWII, and many Texans went on to fame, including Dwight Eisenhower, Chester Nimitz and Audie Murphy. As part of the national engagement effort for Ken Burns' The War, KACV conducted a two-year campaign to capture the stories of Texas veterans. They trained staff and students at 30 libraries, museums, senior facilities and schools to conduct and record oral history interviews. More than 300 veterans contributed and more than 1,000 clips were made available on the station web site. The station worked with ten local teachers to develop lesson plans about WWII, and produced a traveling exhibit featuring photographs taken of and by the veterans, which was used more than 50 times. On-air, the station produced World War II: The Panhandle Project and A Cathedral in the Desert: the POWs of Hereford Camp 31.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;P.O. Box 3000&lt;br&gt;Binghamton, NY 13902&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In partnership with the Broome Community College Center for Civic Engagement, WSKG hosted a series of forums throughout the Binghamton region asking citizens to share both concerns and aspirations for their cities and neighborhoods. These discussions continue to shape WSKG's local program development.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1515 E. Tropicana Ave. Suite 240&lt;br&gt;Las Vegas, NV 89119&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Responding to the need to create a sense of community among the diverse people in Las Vegas, KUNV launched Vegas Voices. Combining music from local performers with oral histories of new and long-time residents, the project has produced an audio CD and a robust web site.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;360 Egan Drive&lt;br&gt;Juneau, AK 99801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (Radio)(CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;To address the health needs of low-income Juneau residents including Alaskan natives, KTOO partnered with seven local non-profits on Take One Step. The project included health surveys, shared meals, information meetings, audio postcards and even a community garden.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;6450 Corporate Drive&lt;br&gt;Johnston, IA 50131&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Current economic conditions have resulted in declining farm income, loss of off-farm jobs, tighter credit due to turbulent agricultural conditions, and a dramatic increase in nonperforming rural loans across the Midwest. With net farm income anticipated to plunge 33% in the next year, Iowa Public Television will reach out to struggling farming families with its initiative "Rural America and the Economic Crisis." The station is planning four town hall meetings in Iowa, Wisconsin, Nebraska, and Kansas to tie into the existing program Market to Market. IPTV has already attracted local partners for this project, and will be coordinating efforts with NET Television in Nebraska, WPT in Wisconsin, and KTWU and Smoky Hills Public Television in Kansas. Working with the producers of The News Hour with Jim Lehrer, IPTV will also expand Market to Market's Web site as the focal point of project content and activities to provide video segments, streamed live programs, user-generated stories, online polls, a blog, and a resource toolbox compiled with assistance from partner organizations.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1555 James Avenue North&lt;br&gt;Minneapolis, MN 55411&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In these difficult economic times, the gaps between minority and total population unemployment and between high school and college graduates' rate of employment are significantly wider. This is particularly notable in Minneapolis, where the unemployment rate hit 8.2% in February, 2009. Many workers and high school graduates have reported to KBEM-FM that the jobs they were trained for no longer exist, or that they need additional training to compete for jobs in today's workforce. In accordance with its educational mission, the station is putting together an initiative called "Working on Our Futures: Publicizing Post-Secondary Training Opportunities." Students and teachers, who are actively involved in the planning and hosting of KBEM's broadcast schedule, will join professionals from partner organizations in creating radio pieces and online video. Not only will students learn new marketable Web and on-air skills, they will help to spread the word about new job opportunities to an audience of 10,000.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;111 S. Highland AVe&lt;br&gt;Marfa, TX 79843&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In Marfa Public Radio's coverage area, cattle-ranching and railroading have given way to jobs in immigration control and drug enforcement, but unemployment and under-employment typically are double the rate for Texas as a whole. Listeners have indicated their interest in more reporting and analysis of the economic crisis, but their use of employment resources is very low. In response, KRTS-FM proposes to develop, produce, and broadcast the series "Back to Work in Far West Texas," an examination of how its rural, majority Latino workforce is coping with the job disruptions imposed by the economic crisis. Partnering with Workforce Solutions of the Upper Rio Grande, the station will use its weekly financial program to "get the whole community talking" about how to develop better jobs in their community, prepare students and adults for new opportunities, and make the most of the programs available now to help equip its population for the future. With primary Internet access being through the public libraries, WRTS-FM will also expand its Web resources to include a blog and podcasting of content to mobile phone users.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;268 Mast Road&lt;br&gt;Durham, NH 03824-4601&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Awarded to New Hampshire Public Television, Maine Public Broadcasting Network and Vermont Public Television. Northern New England is uniquely challenged by the fact that many of its newly unemployed are older Americans. This aging population is struggling in the current job market, as the jobs available typically don't match workers' years of experience. Building on a long tradition of localism, public media in the tri-state region have joined forces to launch "Making $ense: The Economy and Northern New England." Targeting unemployed/under-employed individuals as well as residents 45+ years of age, the stations will work with partners including AARP and the Workforce Opportunity Council to inform, educate and increase awareness of resources and opportunities across the three states. NHPTV, MPBN, and VPT will sponsor workshops and town hall meetings to discuss financial literacy, specifically retirement portfolios, budgeting, health benefits, and new career strategies. This effort includes the production and broadcast of ten original television episodes with related radio call-in shows, interactive online features, and a centralized Web site.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;5005 Belmont Ave&lt;br&gt;Fresno, CA 93727&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Latinos have long endured institutional job discrimination, the "last hired, first fired" practice and general lack of job protection - and this has been exacerbated by the current economic crisis. With six full-power stations in the agricultural centers of California and some 100 affiliates in the United States, Puerto Rico and Mexico, Radio Biling_e is well-positioned to bring news and information to an audience often overlooked by more mainstream news outlets. While the current economic crisis has greatly impacted the Latino working population nationwide, in California the suffering is the greatest, with widespread drought causing the unemployment rate in some counties to top 40%. In response, Radio Biling_e plans to launch "Access to Unemployment Help" using an existing monthly Spanish-language talk show, frequently aired messages, expanded Web activities, and community outreach. The network will highlight the voices of people navigating new or chronic unemployment, connecting them with local, state and national resources, and promoting civic involvement and solutions.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1089 Bannock Street&lt;br&gt;Denver, CO 80204-9972&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;One of the crucial ripple-effect issues Coloradans are facing is the collapse of healthcare coverage as jobs are being lost, company-paid insurance expires, the state cuts back on funding for assistance programs, and individuals can no longer afford coverage. Five years ago, Rocky Mountain PBS (RMPBS) began investigating the difficulties that minorities in Colorado face in getting good quality healthcare, and the station plans to expand its efforts with "Healthy Impact 2010." This project will comprehensively survey the healthcare systems currently in place across Colorado to bring viewers more insight into how their local systems are serving them, in all regions and at all socio-economic levels. With a goal of reaching 40% of the state's households, RMPBS and its partners in public radio and commercial television will coordinate and organize phone banks, town hall meetings, and outreach with health care providers to tie in with television and radio content.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1151 Stadium Dr&lt;br&gt;Cookeville, TN 38502&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The Upper Cumberland region of Tennessee boasts hundreds of century-old family farms, and farmers' markets thrive in all fourteen counties. Organizations such as the Farm Bureau, USDA Rural Development, and the Tennessee Tech University have programs for both consumers and producers to enhance their ability to stretch a dollar and impact their neighbor by buying locally. What the area lacks is a coordinated communication and outreach effort. So WCTE proposes, in partnership with these organizations and the magazine Local Table, a year-long campaign called "Live Green and Prosper" to connect local consumers interested in a sustainable lifestyle with the farmers who can help to provide it. The station will work bring viewers together with its partners through education, outreach, a monthly magazine show on-air, online, in print and social networking opportunities. "Live Green and Prosper" aims to not only help keep small and medium farms afloat, but also to help lower the current unemployment rate of 12.7%.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4 Global View&lt;br&gt;Troy, NY 12180&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Awarded to WMHT and WCNY. The Greater Capital and Central New York regions are facing increasing unemployment as the economic crisis spreads, particularly in their vital manufacturing and financial sectors. WCNY's Oswego County reports the highest rate - 10.9% - in the state. Foreclosures are up 500% in the Albany region, and demand for food stamps has risen 32% in the Syracuse area. Residents at all educational and professional levels are seeking jobs, and WMHT and WCNY aim to assist with their multi-media project "Help Wanted." With community partners' assistance, the stations have identified four major areas of concern: finding jobs, workforce training, protecting consumers, and family financial planning. "Help Wanted" will consist of a 26-episode television series, with related content on other platforms and a strong Web presence, highlighting 52 diverse individuals who will be connected to employment and financial planning resources. Community partners including the New York State Government, local libraries, the Workforce Development Institute, and local NBC and CBS affiliates will help to plan related workshops, host financial training, and update employment listings and resources online, including on Facebook and YouTube.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;158-158A Hexpiece Hill Sub Base&lt;br&gt;St. Thomas, VI 00801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The nation's economic crisis and the rising price of oil have begun to critically affect the Virgin Islands (VI) in the cost and availability of fresh produce. Residents are almost completely dependent on imports, spending more than $74 million in 2007 to import food from the US mainland - the majority of which was vegetables. WTJX-TV proposes, in its project "Home Grown", to encourage residents to grow their own produce and ultimately save money, eat more healthily, and contribute to the greening of the Virgin Islands. Partnering with the Virgin Islands Department of Agriculture (DOA) and the University of the Virgin Islands Corporate Extension Services (CES), the station will assist residents in creating their own successful home-based gardens. The partners will provide the materials necessary to the selected applicants, along with continued technical assistance and guidance to ensure successful "Home Grown" crops. WTJX will film the process from inception to harvest and meal, to be broadcast in a 15-segment series in 2010. A print manual will be assembled for use by viewers, along with YouTube instructional videos and Facebook updates.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1375 Euclid Ave&lt;br&gt;Cleveland, OH 44115&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Economic Response Grants (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Unemployment in the greater Cleveland region recently jumped 55% - the highest in 25 years. In response to this crisis, WVIZ/PBS and 90.3 WCPN ideastream_ plan to expand their multi-media content by tracking the lives of 88 unemployed Northeast Ohioans from a cross-section of the economy through a new program, working title Project HELP WANTED. As a tie-in to this project, the stations will connect their audiences to information and resources provided by a network of trusted community partners including Cleveland's The Plain Dealer, the YWCA, local libraries and universities, and the Ohio Department of Jobs and Family Services. Initiatives will include a town meeting, themed discussion on weekly radio talk-shows and call-in programs, print ads, job listings posted on the Web, as well as blogs and videos from the audience.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;350 S Donaghey&lt;br&gt;Conway, AR 72034&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Seniors constitute AETN's largest demographic, and are one group particularly affected by the current national economic recession. The station focused on teaching financial literacy and providing seniors with advice by airing a primetime special in July 2009 where viewers called in to ask questions of a panel of financial experts. Working with its local partners, AETN produced and documented a "Protecting Arkansas' Seniors" workshop and a "Share Your Story" online component to educate, initiate dialogue and offer access to resources.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1910 University Drive&lt;br&gt;Boise, ID 83725&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;After a five-year boom, 2009 found Idaho fourth in the nation in home foreclosure, with unemployment rates doubling and record numbers applying for food stamps. In response, KBSU launched "Idaho's Economy in Transition." The Program examined how local communities were addressing economic issues when state services were being cut. The station hosted town hall meetings to discuss poverty, hunger and homelessness, aired reports on "Morning Edition" and took testimonials from listeners. Using this information, Boise State Radio helped develop a white paper on poverty in the Boise area, and offered podcasts and additional materials online.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;300 N. Goodwin Ave.&lt;br&gt;Urbana, IL 61801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging Communities on the Economy (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Acting on its commitment to becoming a community convener for Vermilion, Macon and Champaign Counties, WILL held community meetings with the general public and direct service providers in each county. Radio and television producers, as well as major gifts and community engagement staff at WILL, interviewed key organizations to determine the counties top three needs and how the economy is affecting those needs. This research informed the station's weekday call-in programs "Focus 580" and "The Afternoon Magazine," and helped to establish WILL as a resource for its community.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;One Bear Place #97296&lt;br&gt;Waco, TX 76798&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Preparing Waco for the DTV Transition A large part of KWBU's viewing area in and around Waco, Texas is rural and without cable or satellite access. With the DTV transition approaching, KWBU took the lead on providing citizens with information about the improved digital television signal and the new reception equipment required. The station created a series of promo spots explaining the various options for receiving and displaying DTV signals in the home. A 30-minute program about the DTV transition runs regularly on-air. The station provides information on its website, and has printed educational materials to distribute during outreach events, screenings and for anyone who phones or emails with questions or concerns. Showing its strong ties to community, KWBU has responded to hundreds of calls from local viewers and has even sent out its engineer to help with installations.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1 Center Street, 27th Floor&lt;br&gt;New York, NY 10007&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Community Arts Programming on NYCTV Independent artists frequently struggle to expand their audience and music fans have trouble finding indie and underground artists using the mainstream media. Hyper-local broadcaster NYCTV has bridged this gap by actively seeking and soliciting community-based musicians, performance artists and film makers for its original programs Backdrop NYC, Gigs, New York Noise, and Video Music Box. NYCTV's arts programs have won 33 New York Emmy Awards, 42 Telly Awards and six Promax Awards.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7403 N. Kelley Avenue&lt;br&gt;Oklahoma City, OK 73113&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;OETA Voter Voices As a statewide network with a commitment to stimulate civic engagement amongst its diverse regions and populations, OETA was well positioned during election of 2008 to find and aggregate voter concerns. In the months leading up to the election, OETA produced and aired 44 short Voter Voices segments, featuring individual Oklahomans from around the state, speaking about issues important to them and what it would take for candidates to earn their votes. Voter Voices segments were presented on a project website, where others could upload their thoughts, and link to key voter resources. The station also hosted workshops for first time voters, and provided in-depth election coverage on its Oklahoma News Report, the state's only statewide newscast.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;901 S. National&lt;br&gt;Springfield, MO 65897&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Sense of Community Ozarks Public Television and KSMU align their local content development with the needs of southwest Missouri through their Sense of Community Initiative. The initiative is built on the five public interest areas identified in the mission of Missouri State University: Education, Health, Business and Economic Development, Science and the Environment, and Creative Arts. Each year, the stations create one or more 30-minute specials under each area, and address issues in local current affairs programming. This year's business topic was personal financial planning, with the stations producing a call-in show with financial experts. The Sense of Community initiative also helps the stations map their work to the interests of local community foundations and non-profits.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1101 George Rogers Blvd.&lt;br&gt;Columbia, SC 29201&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Generations of Heroes South Carolina has a large military population and long legacy of service. To pay tribute, and to preserve part of the state's history, SCETV worked with the South Carolina National Guard, American Legion Post #6 and students from Richland Northeast High School's to gather firsthand recollections from veterans, civilians and soldiers who have served the United States from World War II until today. Students learned both oral history and digital media techniques, and the 19 mini-documentaries they produced covering the gamut of military experience are available online for teachers and scholars to access.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;555 N. Dakota Street&lt;br&gt;Vermillion, SD 57069-5000&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Tune into Democracy, Tune into SDPB In South Dakota a sprawling state with a small, mostly rural population there are few central resources for civic engagement and awareness. Especially isolated are residents of the state's nine reservation/tribal areas. In response, SDPB partnered with the state Legislative Research Council, Bar Association, Newspaper Association and AARP to develop Tune Into Democracy. SDPB provided gavel-to-gavel coverage of legislative sessions, candidate debates for state and local offices, and election information on radio, TV and in a comprehensive one-stop web site. The need for this information was clearly high, with traffic on the legislative and election Web pages quadrupling during the project.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;172 East Fourth Street&lt;br&gt;St. Paul, MN 55101&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Addressing Community Needs through the Minnesota Channel In 2003, TPT founded the The Minnesota Channel to produce digital content in partnership with other non-profit organizations, with a strong emphasis on untold stories and underserved audiences. To date, TPT has partnered with more than 175 organizations to create more than 480 broadcast programs. Three recent projects showcase TPT's editorial vision and commitment to community: Iraq Vets Return Working with the Minnesota National Guard, TPT produced a set of five broadcasts focused on helping troops, families, medical providers and communities better understand and adapt to the needs of Iraq veterans; SIDA sin Miedo To address an emerging HIV epidemic among Hispanics in Minnesota, TPT worked with Hennepin County's Ryan White Program and with health care providers from West Side Community Health Service's La Clinica to create multiplatform initiative SIDA sin Miedo or Aids without Fear; Close the Gap After a Brookings Institute report revealed that Minnesota had dramatic and growing disparities based on race, class and place, TPT partnered with the Itasca Project to share these findings and to change the state's prospects with a five-part documentary series, community screenings, a curriculum for teens, an extensive website and workforce diversity discussion guide.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Bowling Green State University, 245 Troup Street&lt;br&gt;Bowling Green, OH 43403&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Building A Living Legacy of Hope National Cancer Institute statistics reveal that death rates from cancer in Ohio continue to climb. In response, WBGU-TV and its partners launched an extensive cancer awareness campaign to reinforce that cancer is about hope and survivorship, stress the need for research through clinical trials, build awareness of locally-available standard of care services, and provide cancer survivors isolated in small towns and rural areas with information and support. The team created a Living Legacy of Hope website, sponsored a health event to share information and collect survivor stories and produced on-air documentaries Living with Cancer and The Changing Face of Cancer Research and Clinical Trials. The project helped WBGU forge new community alliances, and sparked funding commitments from local foundations.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Ball State University&lt;br&gt;Muncie, IN 47306-0080&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Living and Aging Well/Make One Change After conducting a day-long town hall with citizens and community leaders about how to best address local health issues, WIPB partnered with Ball State University and the local Boys and Girls Club to help create a wellness education program for children and families. An astounding 21.8 percent of Indiana children are obese six percent over the national average. The campaign, entitled Make One Change, encouraged youngsters and parents to commit to just one adjustment in their daily habits, to reap lifelong health benefits. Make One Change kits were distributed to 28 local schools, with a total of 13,522 student participants. In addition to the K-12 kits, the campaign included billboards, TV interstitials, bus signs, print ads, radio spots, posters, classroom flyers, bracelets for students and a banner for each school to display.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Clement Hall Basement UTM&lt;br&gt;Martin, TN 38237&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;A Lion in the House Community Forum and Outreach Campaign Although cancer is the leading cause of death by disease for youngsters ages one to 19, most communities have little information about its incidence and treatment. Located in rural western Tennessee, WLJT realized that there might also be a lack of resources for families themselves struggling with childhood cancer, and the complex medical issues, emotional problems and financial hardships that accompany it. Using the PBS documentary A Lion in the House as a starting point, WLJT produced cancer awareness interstitials on-air, held a public forum featuring a blue ribbon panel of experts, sponsored a community health fair, and worked with the Nursing Department at the University of Tennessee at Martin to incorporate teaching materials from A Lion in the House into their curriculum.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2400 Olentangy River Road&lt;br&gt;Columbus, OH 43210&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WOSU's Help Your Neighbor with the DTV Transition Campaign When the Department of Commerce suggested that senior citizens would be left behind in the DTV transition, WOSU and local senior organizations took notice. Chuck Gehring, President of LifeCare Alliance commented that 70 percent of our clients live on less than $600 per month, which means most of them simply cannot afford cable television and are in desperate need of the digital converter boxes. Working with partners, WOSU formed a Help Your Neighbor campaign to solicit donations of converter box coupons, receiving more than 2800. The station sponsored Digital Days in their downtown studios to discuss the transition with thousands of seniors and others, assist with coupon applications, and answer installation questions, and provided digital Train the Trainer sessions for social workers at libraries throughout the city.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;5400 N Saint Louis Ave&lt;br&gt;Chicago, IL 60625&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Commitment to the Arts In a city renowned for its love of the arts and its vibrant diversity, WTTW has produced more than 1,300 programs and stories featuring Chicago area musicians, painters, dancers and visual artists, including the Emmy-winning documentary Beauty Rises: Four Lives in the Arts. In 2008, with support from the Illinois Arts Council, WTTW made its extensive archive available and searchable via WTTW Arts Online. The station's commitment continues with its Arts Across Illinois magazine series, where users and viewers can explore the Ballet Folklorico Huehuecoyotl, a Mexican dance troupe formed in Elgin, Illinois, or the Silk Road Theatre project, developed by Palestinian immigrants, or Down on the Farm, an exhibit showing the plight of Illinois' African-American farmers. WTTW is committed to its mission to engage and connect with the rich cultural and intellectual life of Chicago.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1375 Euclid Ave&lt;br&gt;Cleveland, OH 44115&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The Listening Project Each year since 2001, ideastream (comprising WVIZ-TV and WCPN-FM) has used its Listening Project to ask the citizens of Cleveland to identify the assets and challenges of the region to essentially formulate a civic agenda around which the station could develop multiplatform content and services. More than 11,000 people have participated in the discussion, including community leaders, educators and the general public. The Listening Project has led to local documentaries covering the city's foreclosure crisis and the creation of 21st century schools in the region, as well as a performance of the Cleveland Orchestra broadcast on PBS stations around the country. The Listening Project also includes reviews of how well and frequently ideastream reports on issues identified in the previous year. The stations receive high grades for their thoughtful, relevant programming and outreach, and their role in helping the community determine its own future.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1750 Campus Center Drive&lt;br&gt;Kent, OH 44240-5191&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;2010 Moving Ahead: A Forum for Reporting Progress Since the closing of Youngstown, Ohio's many steel mills in the mid-1970s, the city has struggled to compete in the global economy and to maintain a high quality of life for its citizens. In 2003, to ensure a brighter future, city leaders embarked on a comprehensive strategic planning process called Youngstown 2010, and asked Western Reserve Public Media to help communicate progress on the initiative. During the last five years, the station has created 16 programs, covering healthcare, the arts, education, race relations, regionalism and more. They have been watched online and on-air by more than 100,000 residents, and have inspired another 5,000 to participate directly in the city's planning process. Western Reserve Public Media and the city received the American Planning Association 2007 National Planning Excellence Award for Public Outreach.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;821 University Ave.&lt;br&gt;Madison, WI 53706&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Community Impact Award 2009 (TV &amp; Joint)(CPB Funded) &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Wisconsin Hometown Stories In 2007, Wisconsin Public Television began producing Wisconsin Hometown Stories, hour-long profiles of historically significant Wisconsin cities and communities, documenting early history, European settlement, natural resources, population and industrial growth. Each program is accompanied by a History Harvest day, when local residents enjoy a screening of the show and bring along old photos and memorabilia to share with local historians. The completed programs are streamed online, and full interviews and footage are provided to the Wisconsin Historical Society for scholarly review and archiving. K-12 teachers use the programs to develop Wisconsin history lesson plans, and local newspapers frequently run companion pieces. The project has been so popular, and such a powerful way to connect with local communities, that WPT has commited to 30 more documentaries over the next 10 years.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;260 NE 2nd St&lt;br&gt;Grand Rapids, MN 55744&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Three 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KAXE's Citizen Journalism Project tested a model for public radio stations to fund professional quality local citizen journalism content for both broadcast and digital media. Contributions from the public, members, underwriters and online users were solicited to support special series on local news topics.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;5200 Campanile Drive&lt;br&gt;San Diego, CA 92182&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Three 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The KPBS Film Club tested members-only section of kpbs.org with a constantly updated menu of benefits that will leverage their audiences' interest in film. The project evaluated whether offering niche benefits to an online-responsive audience would increase loyalty and donations.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;11767 Owings Mills Blvd&lt;br&gt;Owings Mills, MD 21117-1499&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Three 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Maryland Public Television and ReelChanges.org tested a new revenue stream for public television production by aggregating high-quality documentary projects from a variety of sources and matching them with donors to maximize public financing of program-making.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2601 Mariposa Street&lt;br&gt;San Francisco, CA 94110&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Three 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KQED's Public Media Innovation project leveraged the growth in online audience for its science and nature series, QUEST, by testing a variety of strategies for micro-donations, membership recruitment and messaging.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Kent State University&lt;br&gt;Kent, OH 44242&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Three 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WKSU tested website underwriting strategies for Folk Alley.com. Building on the established Folk Alley audience and social network, WKSU experiment with low cost website underwriting by extending existing ad server software and adding automated self-service underwriting capability.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3025 Walnut Street&lt;br&gt;Philadelphia, PA 19104&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Three 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WXPN and DEI tested the integration of mobile text messaging into established fundraising programs. The project tested a series of in-bound and out-bound messaging techniques to determine how best to raise membership revenue and build opt-in lists of prospects for future fundraising.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;460 Cooper Drive&lt;br&gt;Lexington, KY 40502&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Two (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KET's "Connectivity, Choice and Participation" project tested a wide variety of Web 2.0 strategies to increase secondary school student proficiency and engagement in the study of German.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Washington State University, Morrow Center, RM 382&lt;br&gt;Pullman, WA 99164-2530&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Two (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Northwest Public Broadcasting's "Our Northwest News" tested online game-playing, blogs, wikis and other strategies to engage the audience with regional news stories.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7140 SW Macadam Avenue&lt;br&gt;Portland, OR 97219&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Two (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;OPB's "Invasive Species Online Hotline" employed user-generated content and social networking tools to connect the public with invasive species experts, with the ultimate goal of stopping the spread of invasives in the state.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;100 Innovation Blvd 120 Outreach Bldg&lt;br&gt;University Park, PA 16802&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Two (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Penn State Public Broadcasting's Back from Iraq: The Veterans' Stories Project used a course-based model and Web 2.0 strategies to empower and train Iraq veterans in digital storytelling about the Iraq experience.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Fordham University&lt;br&gt;Bronx, NY 10458&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Two (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WFUV created an online social network for local musicians and music lovers to help them access independent, emerging music.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;One Guest Street&lt;br&gt;Boston, MA 02135&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Two (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WGBH's "Virtual Radio" project launched a branded concert hall/music cafe in Second Life. The project included a live classical music event in a virtual representation of WGBH's new, state-of-the-art live music broadcast studio, the Fraser Performance Studio.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3600 San Jeronimo Drive, Suite 480&lt;br&gt;Anchorage, AK 99508&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Through their "What's Going On in Alaska?" project, KNBA produced a radio and web series on the current economic crisis and its effects in Alaska. The project goal was to build economic and financial literacy in the south-central Alaska community, especially amongst Alaska's Native American population.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;11767 Owings Mills Blvd&lt;br&gt;Owings Mills, MD 21117-1499&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Maryland Public Television's S.C.O.P.E .project (Students Create Original Projects to Educate), was designed to help local school districts enhance and support the existing financial literacy curriculum. High school students created on-line games and other digital media to teach younger students about key financial concepts.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;120 Friday Center Drive&lt;br&gt;Chapel Hill, NC 27517&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;North Country Public Radio's "Common Wealth, Common Wisdom" project connected local young people with depression-era elders, allowing them to share experiences of entrepreneurship in difficult times. The youth and elders shared their stories through audio, video, photos and writing.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2601 Mariposa Street&lt;br&gt;San Francisco, CA 94110&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KQED's "Financial Literacy in the ESL Classroom" created a media-rich online financial literacy curriculum for ESL (English as a Second Language) educators and their adult students, by repurposing existing tools, content, etc. from the public media system and enhancing these with structured lesson plans.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;100 Innovation Blvd 120 Outreach Bldg&lt;br&gt;University Park, PA 16802&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Through its "Responding to the Job Crisis" project, Penn State Public Broadcasting developed a web-centric, map-driven educational resource to help users in central Pennsylvania understand and respond to the job crises in their communities.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;101 Wasatch Drive&lt;br&gt;Salt Lake City, UT 84112-1107&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Through their "Financial Media for Utah Teachers" project, KUEN created a multi-media K-12 financial education website, a week-long series of financial and economic broadcast programs ("Financial Fitness Broadcast Week") and a web-based teacher development program to help meet the state's newly mandated financial education standards.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;821 University Ave.&lt;br&gt;Madison, WI 53706&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Public Media Innovation Grant Round Four 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WECB's "Financial Literacy: PARENT IT" project added a parent component to ECB's teacher development personal financial literacy project. They provided a wide range of online support materials, and produced short videos to model parent-child conversations about key financial issues.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2112 11th Avenue South, Suite 400&lt;br&gt;Birmingham, AL 35205-2884&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;APT bolstered its Alabama-centric science, technology, engineering and math (STEM) education offerings by participating in a national study of whooping cranes. Partnering with the Annenberg Media Initiative, Journey North, and Operation Migration, APT and Title I students across the state tracked the birds' migration to create new STEM content online. Statewide distribution on APTPLUS enabled over 292,000 elementary students in 924 public elementary schools to access the whooping crane curricula.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1 Clover Court&lt;br&gt;Wixom, MI 48393&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;DPT has developed "Think Squad," a weekly half-hour television series to make science, technology, engineering and math exciting and fun for middle-school students. This is vitally important in Michigan, where almost a quarter of the state's 5th graders and nearly half of those in Detroit fail to meet basic science benchmarks on standardized tests. In addition to Think Squad provides viewers and the show's young cast and crew, STEM curriculum and exposure to a variety of science projects, professionals and careers.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;555 N. Central Ave, Suite 500&lt;br&gt;Phoenix, AZ 85004&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Eight's ASSET program experimented with Second Life, a way to bring virtual reality into professional development for K-12 teachers. Virtual field trips, "realtime" workshops, and other online resources dramatically expand how Arizona's educators teach their students and incorporate technology into the classroom. Collaborating with partners ISTE and Virtual Pioneers puts Eight on the cutting edge.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;260 14th Street, NW&lt;br&gt;Atlanta, GA 30318-5360&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Working with the Georgia Department of Education, Georgia Public Broadcasting developed Project ExPreSS to assist high school students with their summer remediation classes. The students focus on science and social studies, with the opportunity of re-taking the high school graduation test at the end of classes. The online modules are self-paced and provide more relevance for the course content, and this approach gets results: participating students in 2009 more than doubled the previous year's pass rate on the state tests.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;6450 Corporate Drive&lt;br&gt;Johnston, IA 50131&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In a recent survey, IPTV discovered that 75% of Iowa middle-school students identified STEM careers as an area they wanted to know more about. As a result, IPTV partnered with Future City, IT Adventures, Iowa Science Fair 2009, IT Olympics, Hyperstream and many other organizations to produce and deliver a series of 113 STEM-related interactive videoconferences to classrooms throughout the state. In 2009 the project reached 655 Iowa schools, with a total of 9,259 teachers and students participating in sessions.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;460 Cooper Drive&lt;br&gt;Lexington, KY 40502&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KET collaborated with the Kentucky Department of Education to expand its CD-ROM and Internet-based professional development resources on literacy instruction. The Literacy Leadership project took cameras into nine Kentucky schools where changes in literacy instruction has resulted in measurable, dramatic improvements among all student demographic groups. This project will assist Kentucky's teachers in learning by watching: it provides interviews and footage in 50 sortable segments to show what effective literacy leadership looks like.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3230 Burt Street&lt;br&gt;Omaha, NE 68131&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KIOS-FM partnered with Omaha Public School District's broadcasting classes to improve students' consistently low-level reading and writing skills. The project taught broadcasting students the basics of newsgathering and reporting using a relatively new form of digital technology, the Marantz PMD-620 Recorder. Enthusiastic about the new equipment and the chance to air their work on-air and online, the young participants were very motivated to improve their reading, writing, and critical thinking skills.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1061 West Temple Street&lt;br&gt;Los Angeles, CA 90012&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KLCS TV, licensed to the Los Angeles Unified School District, has promoted and supported video production in schools for over 20 years. Teachers report that video projects have improved students' ability to demonstrate understanding of course content, as well as increased their motivation and participation in classroom work, resulting in higher student achievement. The Video in the Classroom Competition is an established and respected local contest, further motivating students and their families to participate in video-related class projects.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1200 University Blvd. NE&lt;br&gt;Albuquerque, NM 87102&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KNME has helped to promote science state-wide and organize online resources for high school science teachers. In a state where physics laboratories and high-tech companies are some of the largest employers, KNME's "Science Central" and "Science Crawl" projects are designed to create more public science literacy and encourage middle school students to investigate STEM careers. The station also worked with Albuquerque high school science teachers to develop five new curriculum maps and set up a special e-mail account for the teachers to consult one another with technical questions.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;17011 Beach Blvd, Suite 1550&lt;br&gt;Huntington Beach, CA 92647&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KOCE is the only television station exclusively dedicated to providing news, cultural information, and educational resources to the three million residents of Orange County, which is generally overlooked by Los Angeles media sources. Partnering with Chapman University and the OC Department of Education, KOCE's OC Channel now provides training and an outlet for young filmmakers, as well as become a "one-stop shop" for teacher resources and educational programming on local issues.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;12180 Park Ave S&lt;br&gt;Tacoma, WA 98447&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;As the only exclusive jazz station in the Puget Sound Region, KPLU started its School of Jazz project in recognition that local student musicians needed mentorship in order to succeed. The School of Jazz connects a dozen public high school jazz bands with local jazz professionals so they can practice, learn the secrets of good jazz performance directly from their mentor, and produce a CD that is broadcast on-air and streamed online. So far, more than 1,000 students have participated, and the station has helped to raise over $50,000 for local schools' music programs.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;60th &amp;amp;amp; Dodge Streets, ENGG 200&lt;br&gt;Omaha, NE 68182-0234&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KVNO-FM's Media Unit joined UNO Television to form the Omaha Kids Coalition (OKC), a public service project dedicated to integrating the efforts of nonprofit agencies serving at-risk youth. Broadcasting students from the University of Nebraska Omaha are a large part of the Media Unit's workforce, and provided ancillary OKC work. In using digital media to promote content, students learn how to increase the civic engagement of the publics they serve and foster a climate where citizen journalism flourishes. The OKC project won a 2009 Nebraska Broadcasters Association Award of Excellence in Television, and the students have since produced radio documentaries on obesity and homelessness.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7733 Perkins Road&lt;br&gt;Baton Rouge, LA 70810&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Louisiana Public Broadcasting partnered with the Lafayette Utility System, the Bay Area Video Coalition and the Louisiana Immersive Technologies Enterprise (LITE) to enhance the technology and instruction at Carencro High School. This project provided more bandwidth to the school, expanding instruction to include the creation of 3-D models and training students for careers in technology.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;11767 Owings Mills Blvd&lt;br&gt;Owings Mills, MD 21117-1499&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Partnering with Education Arcade at MIT, animation company FableVision, and an advisory board of state and national math education experts, MPT designed, developed, and delivered "Lure of the Labyrinth". The digital learning game, which aims to help educators teach pre-algebra to middle school students, blends a compelling storyline and puzzles with critical math content to help students learn. In a study of 3,000 students, teachers noted students' increased achievement, engagement, and interest in playing the math game at home. "Lure of the Labyrinth" is available for free on MPT's Thinkport.org.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;One Sesame Street&lt;br&gt;Plattsburgh, NY 12901&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WCFE celebrated the Quadricentennial of Samuel de Champlain's explorations by producing an animated historical documentary for a younger PBS audience. Nearly 1,000 viewers attended the area-wide premieres of "Dead Reckoning: Champlain in America," which was complemented by a newspaper article-writing contest and a comprehensive educational Web site. Lesson plans on geography, information on three local Native American tribes, an interactive map for students to trace Champlain's journey through video, first hand journal accounts, music and timelines remain available for use online.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;100 Innovation Blvd 120 Outreach Bldg&lt;br&gt;University Park, PA 16802&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WPSU's Blue Ribbon Readers program is a series of seven online, interactive literacy games that build skills and confidence in kindergarteners through fifth graders. The project applies research-based approaches to teaching literacy and provides teachers with online resources that engage students. Assessment have clearly demonstrated the value of these evidence-based tools: pre-and post-test scores revealed that on average, students in classes using the Blue Ribbon Readers games gained an oral reading fluency of 17 words per minute and increased their reading comprehension scores by 28 points.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1101 George Rogers Blvd.&lt;br&gt;Columbia, SC 29201&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2008, the Director of the Lowcountry Environmental Education Program, Ian Sanchez, embarked on a kayaking expedition from the mountains to the sea of South Carolina. SCETV's Web of Water is an independently-produced documentary with a companion website, as well as outreach components based on his adventure. This program, which helps students to identify with local natural, cultural and historical landscapes, and to interconnect that understanding in a broader context, was provided to Title 1 schools and groups at-risk or with special needs.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;8401 Datapoint Drive, Suite 800&lt;br&gt;San Antonio, TX 78229&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2006, Texas Public Radio launched their Teaching Tools website, which is designed to help link educators to the specific educational elements, downloadable curriculum and teaching components made available by public radio program producers. For example, programs such as Science Friday, From the Top, StarDate and many others are aggregated on the website, all of which have extensive educational materials available for teachers to use to take the students beyond the story.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;101 Wasatch Drive&lt;br&gt;Salt Lake City, UT 84112-1107&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;First in the nation for home computer use, and with the highest population of children in the U.S., Utah residents are very concerned about the prospective dangers of the Internet. KUEN started NetSafe Utah four years ago to provide in-depth instruction for educators, caregivers and kids through online and in-person workshops. One of the most innovative elements of the program is the addition of short animated videos to address critical Internet safety topics for K-12. In 2009, the program served 24,413 children and 2,462 adults, an eightfold increase over the previous year.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3050 E. Flamingo Road&lt;br&gt;Las Vegas, NV 89121&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Keeping Kids Fit is a three-year project designed to reduce the rate of childhood obesity in Southern Nevada. Using its full educational and technological resources, Vegas PBS educates children and their families about the importance of maintaining healthy body weight and how to incorporate positive changes into their lifestyle in order to do so. Since the program's inception the program's accomplishments include the following: more than 60 workshops have been conducted at the early childhood level; over 400 resource bags (activity guide in Spanish/English, books, DVD, jump rope, measuring cups etc.) have been distributed to Title 1 Tots/Pre K classrooms; and 300 kits (activity guide in Spanish/English, speed rope, resistance band, exercise cards etc.) have been developed to reach 6th grade students at three middle schools in Clark County.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;204 Ethan Allen Avenue&lt;br&gt;Colchester, VT 05446&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Vermont Public Television's contribution to a multi-state initiative celebrating the 400th anniversary of the discovery of Lake Champlain was an hour-long historical documentary, "Champlain: The Lake Between." More than just a program, the project also partnered with several regional organizations to encompass an extensive educational initiative, incorporating public screenings, producer Q&amp;A sessions, teacher training workshops and companion teaching materials on CD-ROM, made available free of charge to schools throughout the region.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;890 Commonwealth Avenue, 3rd Floor&lt;br&gt;Boston, MA 02215&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WBUR's Project Dropout, a multi-part radio series about the Massachusetts high school dropout rate, was a unique collaboration between Boston's two main public broadcasters, WBUR-FM and WGBH-TV. With more than 20 reports airing over two months on both radio and television and a website overseen by both stations, the series helped raise the profile of the high school dropout problem. Project Dropout aired at a crucial time because the Massachusetts Dropout Prevention Commission was drawing up recommendations on how to deal with the dropout problem.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;FSU Broadcast Center, 1600 Red Barber Plaza&lt;br&gt;Tallahassee, FL 32310&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;For four years, WFSU has partnered with the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory to sponsor a science camp for middle school girls called SciGirls, which offers hands-on science experiences. In July 2009, WFSU provided FLIP cameras for the girls to document their experiences. In doing so, the girls reinforced scientific ideas that had meaning for them and were engaged in a wholly unique way.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1630 N. Meridian St.&lt;br&gt;Indianapolis, IN 46202&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WFYI's Indiana Expeditions is a multi-platform series designed to enhance STEM education and inspire interest in science learning. As part of the initiative, the station created six new television shows as well as a complementary website and online teachers' toolkit. The station has used the shows in special trainings at Wayne Township Schools in Indianapolis reaching16,800 students, at ongoing demonstrations at the Indianapolis Children's Museum reaching 12,000 contacts and at professional conferences around the country. More than 20 lessons were videotaped and posted on YouTube and the district's Electronic Video Library.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;44 Hampden Street&lt;br&gt;Springfield, MA 01103&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2009, WGBY piloted the Martha Speaks Read Aloud Book Club, a summer initiative based on the public television program of the same name geared towards inspiring interest in reading for young elementary school children. Through this initiative, approximately 130 children were active participants in a weekly book club, engaging in weekly story readings surrounding the topics and characters of Martha Speaks.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;5200 Hampton Boulevard&lt;br&gt;Norfolk, VA 23508&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WHRO, which is owned by 18 local public school divisions, recently created the Hampton Roads Virtual Learning Center, a regional online school. Through the project, the stations offers modular, instructor-led, core-curriculum online student courses, as well as nearly 40 AP and world language courses with over 3,500 statewide registrations annually.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Horizons Plaza 140 Lower Terrace St&lt;br&gt;Buffalo, NY 14240&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;As part of WNED's Your Life, Your Money Financial Literacy Initiative, the station used the internet and social media to reach out to young adults. Community outreach was built into the project screening events took place in Buffalo, New York City, and Miami, and events are forthcoming in Chicago, Los Angeles and Washington, DC.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;405 Carpenter Street&lt;br&gt;Evansville, IN 47708&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WNIN's Economic Response Phase II initiative, a continuation of a project started in 2008, focused on educating the Evansville-area workforce audience on how to help themselves prepare for their new economic future. Specifically, WNIN prepared five public service announcements (PSAs) on topics including basic needs; first steps for the unemployed; writing resumes/interviewing; 21st Century Skills; and avoiding the depression spiral of unemployment. These interstitials continue to run on TV, radio and online, DVDS are provided for HR departments and social service agencies.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;14901 NE 20th Ave&lt;br&gt;Miami, FL 33261&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WPBT has launched a free, professional development website offers VPK (Voluntary Pre-Kindergarten) educators learning modules that cover four VPK curriculum standards, each of which includes a 5-7 minute virtual field trip taking Pre-K children to different places in the community. Additionally, the station provides 2-3 minute "intro" videos which help teachers understand the standards that are presented in the field trips.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;110 South Jefferson Street&lt;br&gt;Dayton, OH 45402&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Two years ago, Think TV began working with the newly-created regional "STEM" (Science, Technology, Engineering and Math) Center to raise awareness through a series of broadcast image spots about the importance of STEM and the exciting opportunities it offers. The station has developed a strong partnership with the STEM Center, developing web content for students, video for broadcast, and DVD and online professional materials for teachers. WPTD's next step it to collaborate with the STEM Center and our leading arts organizations for a new program on STEM and the arts.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1100 Lincoln Dr - Ste 1003, SIU Mailcode 6602&lt;br&gt;Carbondale, IL 62901&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WSIU is using a multi-platform strategy to reach adult learners with online professional development courses that seek to inspire peer interaction, achievement, and recognition among rural educators in early childhood. The station combines scholarship opportunities, face-to-face orientation, and ongoing local support with the PBS TeacherLine series to introduce teachers to digital learning experiences. Further, WSIU is collaborating with faculty in institutions of higher education to forge new opportunities for online course development and academic credit.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;P.O. Box 3000&lt;br&gt;Binghamton, NY 13902&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WSKG's WoW: Working on Wellness initiative seeks to promote health and wellness issues, namely childhood obesity, in its community, and includes MOVE IT!, an 18-episode WSKG-produced children's television show focusing on health &amp; wellness; as well as Stride with Pride, an outreach program which encourages 3rd to 5th graders to get moving. WoW is aligned with NYS Learning Standards for PE, Math, and ELA. Eight school districts and 870 students participated in the first year, including several Title 1 schools.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1000 College Boulevard&lt;br&gt;Pensacola, FL 32504&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Through its Digital School Initiative, WSRE partnered with the Escambia County School's Instructional Technology department to offer professional development to area K-12 educators, focused on the creative use of technology to enhance the curriculum. The result of the program, in which experts as well as classroom teachers provided hands-on training, was an increased awareness in the community of the innovative ways that area teachers are harnessing the power of technology in their classrooms to help their students learn, achieve and succeed. The television program aired on WSRE and was featured statewide on the Florida Knowledge Network.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;100 Morrissey Boulevard&lt;br&gt;Boston, MA 02125-3393&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;For the past two years, through its The Big Read: Getting Boston Excited About Reading Literature, WUMB deployed a rich array of print and technological resources to stimulate interest in literature. In celebration of To Kill a Mockingbird and Their Eyes Were Watching God, WUMB used its airwaves, website and podcasts for information about the books, interviews with authors and biographers, live call-in talk shows, public service announcements, a radio play and a program of music from the Harlem Renaissance. Over two years, roughly 20,000 reader guides, 650 audio guides, and 385 teacher guides were distributed.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;280 State Street&lt;br&gt;Rochester, NY 14603-3021&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2010 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Homework Hotline is WXXI's live statewide call-in show where primary and secondary school kids receive help with homework problems on WXXI and on public television stations across New York State. In addition to providing homework help, the show presents daily thematic segments on student book reviews, arts, history, science and other subjects. The program's companion Web site earned a 2008 National Parents' Choice Award.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;350 S Donaghey&lt;br&gt;Conway, AR 72034&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;AETN created a spring break family day designed to encourage children to learn and be physically active, through PBS characters, educational games, crafts and contests. The event attracted and engaged 7,000 Arkansas residents, parents, caretakers, teachers and children from diverse communities.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2112 11th Avenue South, Suite 400&lt;br&gt;Birmingham, AL 35205-2884&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;APT serves nearly 48,000 K-12 classrooms with APTPLUS, a dedicated service featuring curriculum-correlated content. APT's E-learning for Educators, created in partnership with its State Department of Education, is used by 75% of Alabama's teachers for online professional development.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;9600 Wright Drive&lt;br&gt;Midland, TX 79708-8940&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In its mission to see that telecommunication and broadcast media are used to advance education, culture and community, Basin PBS partners with the Permian Basin School District to produce a high school academic quiz show that is used by classroom teachers throughout the region, including rural and private schools.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1611 East Magnolia Avenue&lt;br&gt;Knoxville, TN 37917&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Over 4,000 East Tennessee residents have utilized ETPtv's GED programming to obtain a high school equivalency diploma. The station works collaboratively with social service agencies, local colleges and other community organizations to provide this important public service.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4343 Elgin Street&lt;br&gt;Houston, TX 77204&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Aware that 42% of the pre-school population in Houston are at or below the federal poverty line, HoustonPBS conducts train-the-trainer workshops to reach the parents and caregivers of these low-income families. The training is focused on social/emotional development and the importance of early childhood literacy.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;300 N. Goodwin Ave.&lt;br&gt;Urbana, IL 61801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WILL, working to respond to community need, convened town hall meetings where rural teens could address issues impacting their lives. As a result an in-school mentoring program, a mayor's youth council and a new teen center were created. WILL also provides training to urban African American students in media production and journalism.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;6450 Corporate Drive&lt;br&gt;Johnston, IA 50131&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Through IPTV's interactive online learning environment Iowa Pathways, students learn about the history of their state and are challenged to develop Iowa stories suited to their own interests and creativity. The project Web site won the Iowa Distance Learning Association's 2007 Innovator's Award for excellence in K-12 education.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2320 South 19th Street&lt;br&gt;Tacoma, WA 98405&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KBTC was honored by the United Way of Pierce County with the Community Partner of the Year Award for its commitment to early childhood development and education, and for their role in a county-wide effort to guarantee that children in four low-income neighborhoods would begin kindergarten ready to learn.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4401 W. Sunset Boulevard&lt;br&gt;Los Angeles, CA 90027&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KCET's daily program A Place of Our Own/Los Ninos en su Casa and corresponding workshops offer caregivers of young children ways to include learning in their day. Research affirms that 80% of viewers have increased knowledge in key areas such as building literacy skills, identifying children with special needs, and encouraging sharing. To date, 7,000 parents and childcare providers have attended the workshops.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;401 Mercer Street&lt;br&gt;Seattle, WA 98109&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Reflecting their profound ties to K-12 educators, each year KCTS sponsors the Golden Apple Awards for Excellence in Education. Now in its 17th year, the program recognizes innovative teaching models throughout the state, and any teacher, administrator, volunteer or project can be nominated. Winners are featured in primetime specials and online. They also receive financial awards.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;460 Cooper Drive&lt;br&gt;Lexington, KY 40502&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My Source Education Innovation Awards 2009 (CPB Funded)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KET, committed to the role of culture and the arts as a core component of education, developed robust Arts Toolkits for teachers comprising lesson plans, idea cards, glossaries and videos. Since the project began, art scores have shown more improvement than any other tested content area. KET also serves teachers with an extensive Internet-based learning service, KET EncycloMedia, used more than 2.3 million times since 2005.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
