&lt;div&gt;23 Sesame Street&lt;br&gt;Richmond, VA 23235&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Working with the FBI and Local Schools to Increase Internet Safetyﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Community Idea Stations takes its role as a media safe haven for Virginia's children very seriously, recently expanding its efforts to include Internet safety. Internet predatory crime is up 15 to 20 percent in recent years, prompting the FBI to create the Safe Online Surfing (SOS) program for 3rd to 8th grade students. As the FBI struggled to introduce the program to local schools, Community Idea Stations stepped in, correlating the FBI content to mandatory state and federal standards, and developing supplemental materials that made the program more appealing to area teachers and administrators. The result is a pilot program that has potential for national roll-out in 2011.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;300 N. Goodwin Ave.&lt;br&gt;Urbana, IL 61801&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging At-Risk Youth Through Digital Media Production&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2010, Illinois Public Media entered its seventh year of partnering with Champaign-Urbana school districts, the University of Illinois, and other community organizations to improve the academic achievements and attitudes of at-risk African-American high school and middle school students. The Illinois Youth Media Workshop invites young people to become digital producers; students learn to research African-American history, conduct interviews with community elders, and assemble their findings into cogent and compelling stories suitable for presentation on television, radio or online platforms. To date, ten separate projects have involved more than 80 students. The success of these efforts led to the creation of the Youth Media Workshop Summer Institute, an intensive three-day program for teachers.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;6450 Corporate Drive&lt;br&gt;Johnston, IA 50131&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Going Market to Marketﾠwith Rural Economic Summits&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2009-2010, Iowa Public Television's (IPTV) weekly agribusiness series Market to Marketﾠexamined the impact of the recession in rural America with four special programs recorded in Iowa, Wisconsin and Nebraska. For each location, the station scouted regional organizations and experts to appear in televised Town Halls, to discuss risk management, marketing strategies, and the implications of specific government policies on local economic issues. IPTV organized accompanying Resource Fairs, where attendees could learn about resources in their area for employment and economic help.ﾠ This grassroots work was augmented by a robust online engagement strategy that included a content-rich website, online video, story sharing, podcasts and social media.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;4401 W. Sunset Boulevard&lt;br&gt;Los Angeles, CA 90027&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Departures: Capturing the Real Los Angeles Through Transmedia Storytelling&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Departures is KCET's hyper-local web documentary series, community engagement tool and digital literacy program about the cultural history of Los Angeles. Battling media sterotypes about the so-called "city of sprawl," the producers partner with community organizations to create multi-layered portraits of the real Los Angeles. They also train high school students in media production, and teens in turn produce content for the series. Departuresﾠhas received recognition in the press for its innovative storytelling, and is likely to serve as a model for public media productions across the U.S.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;460 Cooper Drive&lt;br&gt;Lexington, KY 40502&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transforming Educational Leadership in Kentuckyﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2009, with educational reform a focus for the state, Kentucky Educational Television (KET) expanded its existing education portfolio to include the emerging link between effective school leadership and increased student performance. Leveraging the national PBS broadcast of The Principal Story, KET created profiles of effective Kentucky principals and administrators for distribution in the education community, and produced a televised panel discussion, a local documentary and robust website. The goals were to provide access to excellent school leadership practices among key education stakeholders, and to broaden awareness of educational reform components overall. These efforts were so successful that KET resources were incorporated into higher education curricula statewide, and the station received funding for a weekly series on education.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;501 Broadway&lt;br&gt;San Antonio, TX 78291-0009&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Celebrating Latina "Firsts" in San Antonio&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KLRN serves one of the largest Hispanic markets in the U.S.ﾠ Insprired by the nomination of Sonya Sotamajor to the U.S. Supreme Court, and Women's History Month, the station developed a high profile awards luncheon called "Celebrating Latina Firsts."ﾠ The event honored ten San Antonio Latinas who have excelled inﾠ fields from education to politics to business.ﾠ Celebrating Latina Firsts attracted many of the most prominent citizens of the region, and the station made sure to invite dozens of high school girls and their teachers to attend the inspirational ceremony. The station took the opportunity to highlight the public affairs programming available on V-me, public media's 24-hour Spanish- language channel carried by KLRN and stations around the nation.ﾠﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2601 Mariposa Street&lt;br&gt;San Francisco, CA 94110&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Taking the Bay Area on a "QUEST" to Improve Science Literacyﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KQED's QUEST puts the Bay Area under the microscope, exploring the stories and people that impact the local science, nature and environmental world. The largest multiple media content project in the station's history, it includes a weekly half-hour HD television program, weekly radio segments, an interactive website, and educational guides. With the expertise of its partners and the Bay Area community, QUEST brings audiences closer to world-class science centers, museums, and the natural beauty of the Bay Area's own open spaces.ﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;The University of New Mexico&lt;br&gt;Albuquerque, NM 87131-1011&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Empowering New Mexico's Youth through Media Production&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KUNM's Youth Radio project provides teenagers with the media production and analysis skills they need to produce a weekly radio show, podcast, online video and blog, and to work in partnership with mentors and a host of local and national partners. The project won the Governor's Award for Youth Service last year, a testament to its place in the New Mexico community as a valued youth resource.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2030 W. El Camino Avenue&lt;br&gt;Sacramento, CA 95812&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sacramento Station Responds to Foreclosure Crisisﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;KVIE launched its Facing the Mortgage Crisis project to build awareness of a staggering dilemma facing its community.ﾠ The station, in partnersip with 2-1-1 Sacramento and other community organizations, connected local residents with resources designed to help them understand, forestall or mitigate foreclosure problems. Partners produced a local town hall TV special, social media (Facebook, Twitter) and a web page devoted to mortage-related issues.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;535 W. William Street, Suite 110&lt;br&gt;Ann Arbor, MI 48103&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A Realistic Portrayal of American Muslims&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With extremist portrayals of the Muslim faith so prevalent in mainstream media, Michigan Radio developed Muslims in Michigan, a community engagement effort designed to paint a more realistic picture of everyday Muslim life, and in so doing, both educate the general audience and reach out to the significant Muslim population in the station's listening area. With community partners, the station developed a five-part radio series,ﾠ two community panel discussions and a content-rich website that includes the archived news stories, an audio/video slideshow, guest essays, and classroom resources. The series and related CD/DVD is available to other public radio stations, libraries and high schools across the country.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Visual Communications Building Montana State University&lt;br&gt;Bozeman, MT 59717&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Providing a Blueprint for Community Planning in Montanaﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With the national rollout of Blueprint America, a multiplatform project focused on transportation infrastructure, MontanaPBS saw a unique opportunity to relate the urban infrastructure issues featured in the project to those in rural America. Working with local government, MontanaPBS engaged the community in the formulation of a Parks and Trails plan that would satisfy the often competing interests of citizens, business owners and land preservation advocates. The station used online surveys, town hall meetings and round tables to solicit community input, and even traveled on foot to get advice from hikers, ATVers, bicyclists, kayakers and equestrians. The result: a plan with overwhelming community support, poised for adoption into law.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3655 Olive Street&lt;br&gt;St. Louis, MO 63108&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Homeland: Meaningful Community Conversations About Immigrationﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The Nine Network of Public Media ﾖ comprising PBS Channel 9 and the St. Louis Beacon online news publication ﾖﾠ is in the midst of an unprecedented multiplatform initiative exploring the complicated issues of immigration. While many media outlets polarize audiences, the goal of this initiative, entitled Homeland, is to use public media to connect and engage people in a meaningful conversation that informs immigration attitudes and policies.ﾠ Homeland's community engagement process includes numerous in-person community meetings around the region (with business leaders, public officials, educators, non-profit representatives, immigrants, refugees and ordinary citizens), and the moderation of a robust online conversation.ﾠ These efforts will inform the content of four one-hour documentaries to be broadcast on PBS in 2011.ﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;7140 SW Macadam Avenue&lt;br&gt;Portland, OR 97219&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Helping Small Business in Rural Oregonﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;With the economic downturn came a severe employment crisis in Oregon, and damage to the state's sizeable rural small business community. Working with community partners, Oregon Public Broadcasting (OPB) developed The Small Business Rural Resource Network Initiative (SBRRNI).ﾠ The goals were to inspire sustainable community building, and raise awareness of resources available to small business owners and the unemployed.ﾠ Through community events, on-air programming, and online content developed by ordinary citizens, SBRRNI showcased the stories of successful entrepreneurs, people trying to make ends meet, and communities working to build stable, vital economies in Oregon's rural towns.ﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;207 North 5th Street&lt;br&gt;Fargo, ND 58102&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;High Risk High: Addressing Underage and Binge Drinking in North Dakotaﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The High Risk High initiative used a website, radio series and local town hall meetings to explore North Dakota's troubling problem of underage and binge drinking.ﾠﾠ Teachers, parents, public officials and students worked together to understand the issues and to bring forth solutions. Prairie Public's multiplatform project garnered a great deal of attention and respect from the press and from government, including a personal endorsement from the state's first lady. The North Dakota Department of Human Services adopted High Risk High as part of the state's alcohol abuse prevention curriculum.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;172 East Fourth Street&lt;br&gt;St. Paul, MN 55101&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Closing the College Graduate/Workforce Gap in Minnesotaﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In response to demographic trends that show the number of high school and college graduates in Minnesota on the decline ﾖ while the state's economy will require nearly twice as many degreed workers ﾖ Twin Cities Public Television's Minnesota Channel produced a thought-provoking documentary called Vanishing Graduates. The program brought together education experts, business leaders and students to explore the state's education challenges, including how to make college more accessible, and the dire implications of the growing gap between college graduates and workforce demands. Station partner Minnesota Private Colleges incorporated Vanishing Graduatesinto their extensive multiplatform public information initiative, LearnmoreMN.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3050 E. Flamingo Road&lt;br&gt;Las Vegas, NV 89121&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keeping Kids Fit in Las Vegas&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2006, research revealed childhood obesity rates in Las Vegas to be well above the national average, especially for Hispanic and African American children from low-income families. In response, Vegas PBS developed the multiplatform, technology-rich community engagement effort Keeping Kids Fit, designed to foster a lifetime of healthy habits. With accessibility a key goal, and with active input from its Community Advisory Council, Clark County Public Schools and others, Vegas PBS designed and distributed curriculum resources to schools and community organizations, facilitated health-focused workshops and events, and launched a robust, highly-interactive web presence with targeted health content for kids, families, teachers and citizens. The station also produced and broadcast extensive health content on-air.ﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;890 Commonwealth Avenue, 3rd Floor&lt;br&gt;Boston, MA 02215&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CommonHealth: A Blog for the Common Good&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;CommonHealthﾠis a comprehensive health care blog produced by Boston public radio station WBUR, in partnership with NPR. The site quickly distinguished itself on the local and national stage through a mix of high-quality news, analysis and community conversation. An interactive map on the site tracks public health outbreaks statewide.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;506 Old Liverpool Road&lt;br&gt;Syracuse, NY 13220-2400&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Helping Syracuse Veterans and Their Families Cope With 21st Century Challengesﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Located in a region with major military installations and veteran's hospitals, and recognizing a lack of productive dialogue around veteran's issues, WCNY embarked on an engagement initiative called Our Veterans and Their Families: 21st Century Challenges. Created in collaboration with local mental health partners, the multiplatform project was designed to connect veterans and their families to resources available to help them, and to raise awareness among the general public regarding the realities faced by the modern veteran.ﾠ The television program profiled everyday stories of soldiers and their families and offered expert insights around issues of redeployment, reintegration, injuries and women in service; a website linked veterans to resources and related online content.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;FSU Broadcast Center, 1600 Red Barber Plaza&lt;br&gt;Tallahassee, FL 32310&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Raising Child Literacy in Tallahassee, Floridaﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;By bringing the PBS KIDS Raising Readers project to the Tallahassee, Florida community, WFSU became a community leader in promoting child literacy. With partners and advocates ranging from the city's mayor to local media outlets and, of course, public schools, Raising Readers has touched thousands of families through a broad range of activities, from summer camps and after school programs to classroom activities and community events.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;One Guest Street&lt;br&gt;Boston, MA 02135&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engineer Your Life: Inspiring Girls to Pursue Careers in Engineeringﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Created to correct incorrect perceptions that engineering is not a field for women, Engineer Your Life (EYL) is a groundbreaking image and messaging campaign spearheaded by WGBH.ﾠ Through extensive research, a content-rich website, a robust online advertising and social media campaign, hands-on training, print materials, and participation in college fairs across the country, EYL has generated impressive results. Eighty-eight percent of girls familiar with EYL say it made them more interested in engineering as a career. EYL has also proven to be an invaluable recruitment tool for engineering colleges and universities, as well as an effective platform around which a coalition of engineering and education organizations have mobilized to change the image of their profession.ﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2222 4th Street NW&lt;br&gt;Washington, DC 20059&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;WHUT Builds Literacy Skills Out of the City and Down on the Farmﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WHUT, the first PBS station operated by a predominantly African-American institution (Howard University), brought children and teachers from under-resourced elementary schools in D.C. out into the Maryland countryside for a day of fun and reading. The station's Word WorldﾠLiteracy Day at Oxon Hill Farm featured presentations about agricultural life from National Park Service rangers, literacy activities usingﾠ farm and animal words, and plenty of fresh air and sunshine.ﾠ In total, 265 children, from some of D.C.'s most at-risk neighborhoods, participated.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;821 University Ave.&lt;br&gt;Madison, WI 53706&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For Vietnam Veterans, Wisconsin is a Welcome Homeﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In 2010, Wisconsin Public Television (WPT) spearheaded a multiplatform community engagement effort to document untold stories from the state's many Vietnam veterans, and to create a place for the entire state to thank them for their service. Along with its Wisconsin Vietnam War Storiesﾠdocumentary, WPT produced a companion book, classroom curriculum, a rich web presence and a series of community events to engage residents in conversations about the Vietnam War. These efforts culminated in LZ Lambeau, a three-day welcome home and storytelling event for veterans that took place at historic Lambeau Field. An estimated 70,000 attended what one participant called "a huge healing ground."&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;822 University Ave.&lt;br&gt;Madison, WI 53706&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A Standing Ovation for Young People and the Arts in Wisconsinﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Recognizing Wisconsin's love of the arts and passion for youth competitions ﾖ and to respond to funding challenges in arts education ﾖ Wisconsin Public Television (WPT) built a major broadcast event around the Bolz Young Artist Competition. The contest is open to high school-aged classical music instramentalists throughout Wisconsin. Working with the Madison Symphony Orchestra (MSO) and Wisconsin Pubic Radio, WPT developed Wisconsin Young Artists Compete: The Final Forte, a free concert featuring the competition's four finalists performing live with the MSO,ﾠ simulcast live on TV and radio throughout the state.ﾠ The strong partnership between WPT and the MSO has helped both to deepen community relationships, secure financial support, and enrich the arts landscape in Wisconsin.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;100 Festival Park Avenue&lt;br&gt;Jacksonville, FL 32202&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mister Rogers Sweater Drive ﾖ Serving Jacksonville's Homeless Populationﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;What started as a nominal sweater drive to honor a PBS icon has for WJCT has evolved into an extensive community collaboration to build awareness and meet the immediate needs of the city's increasing homeless population. Begun in 2002, the WJCT Mister Rogers Sweater Drive mobilizes nonprofits, businesses and schools around a large-scale clothing drive. Local businesses provide financial and logistical support to manage donated items, while nonprofits help distribute clothes to the homeless. Local schools are also involved, providing incentive for students to participate. WJCT chronicles and promotes the event's activities and partners across its many media platforms. With 100% growth each year, WJCT's drive now directly serves more than 2,500 homeless people.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Horizons Plaza 140 Lower Terrace St&lt;br&gt;Buffalo, NY 14240&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Think Bright and Well: Promoting Healthy Lifestyles in Buffalo and Beyondﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Responding to troubling health and wellness statistics in western New York, WNED developed a two-year, multiplatform community engagement initiative entitled Think Bright and Well. The goals: provide access to health and wellness resources and literacy, especially to those in need; and, train community "connectors" to serve as ambassadors for healthy lifestyles within the community.ﾠ Think Bright and Well includes health-focused on-air programming, a content-rich website, and turnkey training resources for use on the ground by community leaders and health professionals. Through a partnership with other public stations, the project's content and activities have been replicated across upstate and western New York. The project may also serve as a prototype for national distribution of wellness content and resources.ﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;405 Carpenter Street&lt;br&gt;Evansville, IN 47708&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Using Media Engagement to Create a Healthier Evansville&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Comprehensive research conducted by the Welborn Baptist Foundation in 2008 pointed to obesity as the key driver of poor adult health in Evansville, Indiana. In response, WNIN developed a multiplatform community engagement effort focused on exercise and nutrition. Using its media and education expertise, WNIN enhanced the Welborn Foundation's existing anti-obesity community and school initiatives. Station staff developed content, curriculum and a health-focused on-air and social media campaign. They worked with additional partners to facilitate community conversations amongst citizens, businesses and local government. WNIN continues to mobilize the community to fight obesity, serving as the primary aggregator of community activities, initiatives and organizations committed to health in the tri-state area.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;161 Rains Avenue&lt;br&gt;Nashville, TN 37203&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nashville Public Television Introduces Citizens to Their Immigrant Neighborsﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Next Door Neighbors is Nashville Public Television's multiplatform content and engagement initiative designed to explore the immigrant community cultures that have developed in Nashville in recent decades. To date, four documentaries have explored the Bhutanese, Somali, Kurdish and Spanish- speaking immigrant communities in the region. All four were nominated for regional Emmy awards, with Little Kurdistan, USAﾠtaking the 2008 prize for Best Historical or Cultural Program. Most importantly, each production was informed by deep, multiple, small scale engagements with both immigrant community organizations and those organizations directly affected by the immigrant communities in some way.ﾠ Each was screened in a public forum with a facilitated panel discussion, and each is frequently streamed from the project website.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;2400 Olentangy River Road&lt;br&gt;Columbus, OH 43210&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Columbus Neighborhoods Project Increases Civic Prideﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;The Columbus Neighborhoods Project is a three-year, cross-platform project designed to generate civic pride as the city ramps up to its bicentennial in 2012.ﾠ Through a series of six documentaries, a robust website that invites citizen storytelling, and a busy calendar of community events, WOSU is creating an authentic portrait of the area's diverse culture and history.ﾠﾠﾠ&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1000 College Boulevard&lt;br&gt;Pensacola, FL 32504&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Celebrating Local Music on Florida's Gulf Coastﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;StudioAmped is WSRE's annual concert series featuring songwriters and musicians from the Gulf Coast region. Thousands of area residents have attended free concerts held in WSRE's Jean &amp; Paul Amos Performance Studio. The performances are televised for broadcast and made available on-demand from the series website. A blog, tweets, Facebook page and collaborations with local newspaper and radio outlets complete the project's multiple platform distribution. StudioAmpedﾠdramatically increases the visibility of Gulf Coast artists and their music, and broadens WSRE's appeal and reach in the community.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;3242 Commonwealth Avenue&lt;br&gt;Charlotte, NC 28205&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;From Station to Community: A Helping Handﾠ&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;In Charlotte, North Carolina, a one-woman powerhouse, Beverly Dorn-Steele, leveraged her visibility as an on-air personality for the local public media station, WTVI, to built a strong relationship between the station and a neighboring low-income housing development, whose residents were in dire need of educational services. Dorne-Steele screened PBS KIDS shows for residents, invited families into the station for tours and events, instituted a GED preparation program with volunteer tutors, began a walking club for women, and organized potluck dinners.ﾠ Over five years, these projects have improved the lives of residents, strengthened neighborhood bonds, and demonstrated the commitment that public stations feel towards their communites.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;1200B Weimer&lt;br&gt;Gainesville, FL 32611-8405&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engaging African American Communities of Faith Around The Misunderstood Epidemic: Depression&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WUFT used the national documentary The Misunderstood Epidemic: Depressionﾠas a springboard for much-needed discussion in Gainesville's African American community.ﾠ Recognizing the influence and importance of spiritual leaders, the station first presented local pastors with information about the prevalence, signs and dangers of depression. After survey results revealed that this initial presentation had convinced pastors that depression was an issue that needed to be addressed by their congregations, the station sponsored additional events to provide information and materials to the broader faith-based community.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;280 State Street&lt;br&gt;Rochester, NY 14603-3021&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Raising 100,000 Voices: Empowering At-Risk Youth in Rochester&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;Each year, WXXI works with a dozen community partners on a large-scale youth media project that helps at-risk young people to confront the difficult transition to adulthood. Emerging from a 2005 project specifically targeting kids "aging out" of the foster care or child services system, Raising 100,000 Voices now engages 100 young people (aged 12 to 24) each year in workshops on the art of video producing, critical thinking and storytelling.ﾠ The end result is dozens of three-minute video pieces that give voice to a population not accustomed to being heard. Their videos deal with diverse topics such as health, rap music, religion, friendship, teen violence, succeeding in high school, prejudice and bullying.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;

&lt;div&gt;111 Veterans Blvd Ste 250&lt;br&gt;New Orleans, LA 70184&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;New Orleans Residents Get an Equal Voice in a National Campaign to End Poverty&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div&gt;WYES has witnessed great deal of assistance coming into New Orleans after Hurricane Katrina. Although this help has been greatly needed, the station knew that the aid recipients ﾖ often disenfranchised ﾖ had not actually been asked what they thought their community needed. The station developed an engagement project around the documentary Raising Hope: The Equal Voices Story. The film chronicles a national effort by the Marguerite Casey Foundation to understand the needs and aspirations of America's diverse, disadvantaged population. In New Orleans, WYES used screenings and facilitated discussions to inspire and empower local residents to advocate for themselves about their health, education and housing needs.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt; 
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/br&gt;
